<F P=100> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Burundi's Envoy Seeks International Aid </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1102143694 Brussels LE SOIR in French 11 Feb 94 p 9 </F>
<F P=103> BR1102143694 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels LE SOIR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed V.K.: "New Government Team in Burundi"] </F>
  [Text] Faced with the continuing explosive situation in the 
country, new Burundian President Cyprien Ntaryamira -- who was 
sworn in last Saturday [5 February] -- and his prime minister, 
Anatole Kanyenkiko, have rapidly formed their new government 
which was announced on Wednesday evening. Including 27 
ministers (compared with 22 in the previous government), 60 
percent of them are drawn from the Frobedu [Burundi Democratic 
Front], the president's party. The remaining 40 percent come 
from the opposition, principally the Uprona [Unity for National 
Progress] and a newcomer, the new Liberal Party. This formula 
had already been adopted by the late President Ndadaye. 
  Jean Ngendanganya, Burundian ambassador in Brussels, 
welcomed 
this re-establishment of democratic institutions and appealed to 
public opinion, friendly governments, and non-governmental 
organizations to help the new government team to rebuild the 
country, deeply marked by recent events. "We have 800,000 
refugees to be repatriated, and just as many displaced persons 
who we must help to return to their homes," he stated, adding 
that -- for greater efficiency -- this government "is mainly 
composed of technicians. These qualities took precedence in 
selecting the future ministers, more than their position in the 
party hierarchy. It is also clear that the services of those who 
took part in the attacks were not retained." 

</TEXT>

