<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EC's Delors Hopes NATO Ultimatum Can Advance Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1202100094 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 0900 
GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1202100094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Does Jacques Delors -- who has not reacted yet to 
the NATO ultimatum -- agree with NATO's pressure? This is the 
European Commission president's response, as recorded by Michel 
Barthelemy: 
  [Begin Delors recording] Given the point reached in the 
conflict, I would like to take my responsibility and say yes, 
hoping that this pressure would allow the peace process -- which 
is close to fruition -- to resume. This involves a 2 percent 
readjustment of the Serbian territory in order to allow the 
Muslims to have a viable state. The Bosnian Serbs and Croats 
have obtained satisfaction. Therefore, this pressure is part of 
the peace process. 
  I regret that a solemn warning had not been given before to 
those who have introduced the ideology of death that is ethnic 
cleansing. Today, things are what they are. Let us not return 
to the past. There is no point in doing so. I hope that this 
pressure will make everyone think and realize that they have 
more to lose than gain in pursuing the conflict. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

