<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials React to NATO Decision on Bosnia Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<H4>   Ciller Says Turkey Supports Decision </H4>
<F P=102> TA1002122694 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1100 
GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1002122694 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Tansu Ciller has said that Turkey 
views positively and supports the decision NATO made on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina yesterday. 
  In a statement prior to the True Path Party General 
Administrative Council meeting, Ciller said Turkey has for a 
long time been defending the need to preserve 
Bosnia-Herzegovina's territorial integrity and to respect human 
rights. Pointing out the need to lift the arms embargo or to 
launch an air raid to achieve that goal, Ciller recalled that 
Turkey had submitted this plan to the United Nations. She 
continued: 
  [Begin Ciller recording] We had earlier proposed that the 
Serbs positioned on the mountains surrounding Sarajevo be moved 
back 20 km and that they surrender their arms. We had also 
proposed that an air raid be launched in the event they did not 
comply with these conditions -- in other words, that a 
transition period be established prior to the air raid. We 
support this decision made by NATO. We believe that it is 
positive. [end recording] 
  Ciller said the violence is continuing in Bosnia-Herzegovina 
and humanity is waging a struggle for life and dignity. Pointing 
out that the innocent people of Bosnia-Herzegovina should either 
be given the opportunity to defend themselves or be protected, 
Ciller added that the NATO decision is a significant step in 
this direction. Noting that during her contacts with various 
leaders she was informed that such a development would occur, 
Ciller concluded by saying: 
  [Begin Ciller recording] I hope that a better solution will 
be reached through peaceful means within 10 days. We will stand 
by this decision to the end. I would like to state once more 
the need to begin the air raid immediately if any clashes take 
place. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

