<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials React to NATO Decision on Bosnia Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<H4>   Cetin Stresses NATO `Credibility' </H4>
<F P=102> TA1002125594 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1100 
GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1002125594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over still of Cetin] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin has expressed the 
view that the NATO decision reached on Bosnia-Herzegovina 
yesterday is significant in many aspects. 
  In a statement today, Cetin stressed that the decision is 
important from the viewpoint of the alliance's credibility and 
relations between North America and Europe. He said: We 
sincerely hope this decision will at least prevent further 
massacres and facilitate a solution in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
Cetin recalled that Turkey prepared a similar plan in August 
1992, and presented it to the five permanent UN Security Council 
members. He continued: From that moment on, Turkey has 
defended it views on the issue at every forum. When we look 
back, we see that it would have been preferable to reach a 
similar decision then, thus preventing the death of thousands of 
people. Diplomacy that is not supported by a convincing 
determination cannot succeed. This principle has once again 
been confirmed in Bosnia-Herzegovina. Now what remains to be 
done is to implement the decision without any changes and speed 
up efforts toward a solution. Turkey will continue to fulfill 
its duties on the issue. 

</TEXT>

