<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Views PFP Document, Bosnian War </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402182294 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1700 
GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1402182294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Aleksandur Vladkov in Brussels on </F>
Zhelev's news conference before his departure for Sofia -- live 
or recorded] 
  [Text] [Announcer] President Zhelev signed a framework 
agreement on cooperation with NATO in Brussels today. Before 
departing for Bulgaria, he gave a news conference for Bulgarian 
and foreign journalists. Let us hear the following report by 
our West Europe correspondent Aleksandur Vladkov. 
  [Vladkov] The Bulgarian president described the signing of 
the Partnership for Peace [PFP] agreement as an essential 
element in a very important process. He described the agreement 
as an introductory stage to the future integration of Bulgaria 
and the other East European countries as full members, on the 
one hand, and as the beginning of NATO's transformation into a 
collective, continental security structure, on the other hand. 
  The agreement is a challenge for speeding up the reforms in 
our country under a military-political aspect and under purely 
economic and social aspects. However, it is also a challenge 
for NATO in connection with the adjustment of the organization 
to the new realities in Europe and the world in the direction of 
a universal collective security structure, rather than in the 
direction of isolated military-political blocs. 
  Dwelling on the crisis in Yugoslavia and on the war in 
Bosnia, President Zhelev pointed out as follows: The conflicts 
in the immediate vicinity of our border are directly challenging 
our national security and are causing immeasurable difficulties 
for our economic reform, because of the international sanctions. 
  Nevertheless, Bulgaria's policy remains well-intentioned, 
peace-loving, and based on moral principles. I am sure that all 
civilized, democratic countries will duly appreciate it. 

</TEXT>

