<H3> <TI>   Italian UN Envoy: Negotiation `Only Way' for Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1502104594 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2205 GMT 14 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1502104594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bosnia: Negotiation Only Way to </F>
True Peace, Italy Tells UN"] 
  [Excerpt] New York, 14 Feb (ANSA) -- Durable peace in 
Bosnia can only be achieved through negotiations which reach an 
overall and just agreement between all parties involved, Italy's 
ambassador to the United Nations, Francesco Paolo Fulci, said 
during the marathon session of the United Nations Security 
Council here on the Balkan conflict. 
  Ambassador Fulci went on to argue how an eventual air-strike 
in and around Sarajevo, if the siege of the Bosnian capital is 
not removed by February 20, "should not be viewed exclusively as 
an act of reprisal or a response to the deadlock in the peace 
process, but as a means to induce the sides to return to reason 
and make every effort possible to come to an agreement." The 
Italian diplomat then went on to stress the importance of 
Italy's active role in the adoption of the ultimatum which 
represented the "point of change in the attitude of the 
international community towards the crisis in Bosnia" and a 
"catalyst for new contributions in the search for a political 
solution." 
  In his address, Ambassador Fulci reiterated how Italy has 
put 
its military bases and airports at the full disposition of the 
Atlantic Alliance for any action in Bosnia. 
  The Italian ambassador concluded by making a host of 
appeals, 
asking that opposing forces in Bosnia "exercise moderation and 
demonstrate political will to reach a negotiated settlement," 
extending this plea to "anyone who can influence the warring 
factions with renewed vigor." He then called on those countries 
participating in the UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] contingent, 
humanitarian organizations, international agencies and "all men 
of good will" to not waiver in their efforts. "A peaceful 
solution for Bosnia can be found" Ambassador Fulci said, "but 
only if we all persevere." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

