<H3> <TI>   Metalworkers Wage Talks Fail; No New Date Set </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1102211094 Hamburg DPA in German 1935 GMT 11 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1102211094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] After over 10 hours, the top-level talks held in 
Darmstadt to avert strikes in the west German metal and 
electrical industries failed on Friday [11 February]. The 
representatives of the IG Metall trade union and the 
Gesamtmetall employers organization parted in the evening, 
without agreeing on a date for fresh talks. 
  Gesamtmetall's president, Hans-Joachim Gottschol, blamed the 
trade union for not accepting the employers' proposals on 
securing jobs. The employers had suggested opening up wage 
agreements, which would have allowed companies to increase work 
time to 40 hours, or decrease it below the current 36 hours per 
week on a temporary basis. IG Metall had rejected longer 
working hours and demanded wage compensations in the event of a 
shorter working week, which would be counterproductive on the 
labor market, Gottschol said. 

</TEXT>

