<F P=100> BENELUX </F>
<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ter Beek Backs Use of Air Strikes in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1402140894 Rotterdam NRC HANDELSBLAD in Dutch 11 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> BR1402140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rotterdam NRC HANDELSBLAD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Ter Beek Still Considering Defense </F>
of UN Troops Adequate"] 
  [Text] The Hague -- Defense Minister Ter Beek is convinced 
that the Dutch troops can defend themselves adequately in 
Bosnia, even if tension rises as a result of airstrikes around 
Sarajevo. 
  During a 10 February television program, he said it was very 
important that the UN commanders on the spot be able, in 
agreement with UN Secretary General Butrus-Ghali's 
representative, to decide quickly to request air support for 
their self-defense. In Parliament last week, Ter Beek labeled 
the possibility of requesting air support "an additional 
precaution for our ground forces." 
  Organizations of draftees are concerned about the 
consequences the NATO ultimatum and the threat of air strikes 
could have for the Dutch military in Bosnia. They say that this 
threat involves a shift of tasks and powers, because the UN 
troops are no longer deployed exclusively for peacekeeping 
operations, but also for peacemaking operations. In Bosnia, 
there will soon be some 500 draftees out of a total of 2,000 
troops. They volunteered for this mission. 
  Ter Beek disagrees with the interest groups. The job of the 
Dutch military did not change after NATO's decision. The Dutch 
are deployed in Bosnia to carry out humanitarian tasks, and 
their assignment and rules of engagement are unchanged: Force 
can only be used in self-defense, and for defending the 
population of the "safe areas" of Zepa and Srebrenica when it is 
at risk. 
  Should tension in the field rise as a result of the air 
strikes, ground forces can be concentrated in one place, so that 
they can defend themselves more efficiently. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

