<F P=100> CANADA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ouellet Discusses `Special Partnership' with ROK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1502064294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0245 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1502064294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ottawa, Canada, Feb. 14 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and 
Canada agreed Monday [14 February] that they will form a special 
partnership for cooperation in trade, economic and regional 
development, and in international organizations. 
  Seoul-Ottawa trade cooperation anticipates South Korea's 
participation in the North American Free Trade Agreement 
(NAFTA), said Korean officials who are accompanying Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu on a visit to Canada. 
  Han held talks with his Canadian counterpart Andre Ouellet 
here Monday afternoon at which the Korean foreign minister 
expressed his country's desire to form a special relationship 
with NAFTA members. 
  Ouellet promised Han that Canada will actively study the 
South Korean proposal, according to the Korean officials. 
  Han briefed Ouellet on the positions of South Korea and the 
United States on the North Korean nuclear problem and asked for 
Canada's continuing support for resolution of the issue, they 
said. 
  Prior to visiting Ottawa, Han held talks with U.S. 
Government 
leaders on the North Korean problem in Washington. 
  Han and Ouellet shared the opinion that their countries, 
both 
surrounded by economically powerful neighbors, can work together 
and complement each other. They agreed to foster conditions for 
partnership in all fields, the officials said. 
  Han later met with Minister for International Trade Roy 
Maclaren and discussed trade promotion and economic cooperation. 
"They have agreed to form a partnership in political, economic, 
trade and other fields," the officials said. 
  The special relationship calls for an increase in trade, 
cooperation in regional and global issues, and efforts to 
achieve peace and security in the Asia-Pacific region and the 
world. 
  With regard to the North Korean nuclear issue, Ouellet said 
it is obvious the world does not want to see any country 
withdraw from the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty (NPT). 
  He said Canada supports South Korean and U.S. efforts to 
resolve the issue through dialogue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

