<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   IG-Metall, Gesamtmetall Explain Failure of Wage Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402180894 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 14 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1402180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["df"-attributed report: "Parties to the Wage Negotiations </F>
Have Given Up `Taboo' Positions"] 
  [Text] Duesseldorf, 12-13 February -- In talks with 
HANDELSBLATT Klaus Zwickel, chairman of the IG-Metall trade 
union, and Dr. Dieter Kirchner, general manager of the 
Gesamtmetall employers' association, explained why the top-level 
talks about the conclusion of anew collective agreement in 
Darmstadt failed. 
  Both parties to the wage negotiations gave up their previous 
taboo positions in Darmstadt. Giving up the vacation bonus or 
reducing wage costs by 15 percent hardly played a role, just as 
IG-Metall showed only little interest in wage raises. 
Gesamtmetall was willing to agree to a drastic shortening of 
work time on the condition that the working people renounce wage 
compensation; IG-Metall wanted to agree to that only if entire 
work forces were to work less than 35 hours per week, but not in 
case of a differentiation of work time between groups of working 
people within a company. 
  Agreement could have been reached about advancing the 
introduction of the 35-hour workweek, which has been agreed on 
by collective agreement as of 1 October 1995, since IG-Metall 
was willing to compensate the employers for the resulting costs. 
The collective agreement on opening clauses, which permit the 
companies to deviate from the collective agreement regarding 
work time regulations, was no problem anymore. IG-Metall was 
willing to offer an annual work time on the basis of a 35-hour 
workweek, which would have given the employers options with a 
range of 30 to 40 hours per week, if the regular work time had 
been adhered to on the annual average. 
  Despite these concurrences of the mutual negotiating 
positions, the top-level talks in Darmstadt failed because 
IG-Metall did not want to give up graduated wage compensation in 
a case of shortened work time for partial work forces. The 
IG-Metall Executive Committee now wants to explain the failure 
of the negotiations on 21 February and to hold a strike ballot 
on the possibility of a strike. There will probably be no 
further top-level talks before this date. 
  After the beginning of the strike, the instrument of 
"Special Arbitration" would then be applied, within the 
framework of which Gesamtmetall and IG-Metall would try to 
settle the wage conflict under the chairmanship of an arbiter, 
who would be decided on either by drawing lots or by agreement. 
It is assumed that such a development is necessary also so that 
the two parties to the wage negotiations can avoid internal 
pressure from their members, to which they are still subject to 
at the moment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

