<H3> <TI>   Streibl Confirms `Private Visit' With Schoenhuber </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402154794 Berlin DIE WELT in German 14 Feb 93 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1402154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hannes Burger: "Streibl Confirms Meeting With </F>
Republikaner Chairman"] 
  [Text] Munich -- Former Bavarian Minister President Max 
Streibl, Christian Social Union [CSU], has confirmed to DIE WELT 
that he received Republikaner Chairman Franz Schoenhuber for a 
private visit last November. 
  Schoenhuber was the one who wanted the meeting, Streibl 
said. 
Since his decade-long personal contact with Schoenhuber had 
never been interrupted, he told himself: "Why not?" After all, 
after his resignation as minister president, he has had a number 
of talks with politicians from other parties. 
  The contents of this personal talk with Schoenhuber was 
"neither secret nor political." They primarily discussed joint 
memories of the time when both of them worked closely with Franz 
Josef Strauss and Edmund Stoiber. Streibl denied any intention 
to leave the CSU and even to join the Republikaner. Streibl: 
"Schoenhuber did not try to persuade me at all." 
  Bavarian Culture Minister Hans Zehetmair was "completely 
surprised" about Streibl's contacts with the Repulikaner. On 
the private SAT-1 television station, Zehetmair said that the 
Republikaner are the declared opponents of the CSU. 

</TEXT>

