<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Post-GATT Situation Discussed by Sector </TI></H3>
<H4>   * Maritime Sector Analyzed </H4>
<F P=102> 94ES0228E Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS in French 17 Jan 94 p 
12 </F>

<F P=103> 94ES0228E </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS interview with Eric Giuily, president </F>
of the General Maritime Company (CGM), the publicly-owned 
"leading" French shipowner; place and date not given: "Finding 
European Alliances"] 
  [Text] [LE QUOTIDIEN] What is your analysis of the status 
quo that has been confirmed by the GATT accords? 
  [Giuily] The American and Japanese protectionist systems, 
which work to the disadvantage of the European shipowners, have 
indeed been retained. But the freeing up of the markets, to 
which we are committed in order to reestablish a certain 
balance, could have challenged certain market organization 
principles (with the shipowners' associations) that we would 
hope to maintain. 
  [LE QUOTIDIEN] What do you plan on doing with regard to the 
foreign competition on your traditional markets? 
  [Giuily] We must improve our competitive capacity and reduce 
our costs. Our strategy will also be based on alliances with the 
European shipowners--the Bollore group's SDV, or others. But the 
opening up of the American and Asiatic markets should in any 
case be negotiated. The European Community should not propose 
additional liberalization on a unilateral basis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

