<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Editorial Views U.S Lifting of Vietnam Embargo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0902160294 Madrid YA in Spanish 4 Feb 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> PM0902160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid YA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Clinton, Eastward"] </F>
  [Text] Bill Clinton's Far East policy has taken another 
step in lifting the trade embargo which the United States kept 
imposed on Vietnam, thus ending three decades of hostilities 
with that Southeast Asian country. It is a decision consistent 
with the lines of opening to the enormous markets of the Pacific 
and Indian Ocean countries laid down by the Free Trade Treaty. 
  The fall of the Berlin Wall, the coming together of the two 
Europes, the end of apartheid in South Africa, the understanding 
between Jews and Christians in the Vatican and Jerusalem, and 
the agreements between the Israelis and the PLO -- to cite the 
most celebrated rapprochements -- have created a world 
atmosphere of peace and the elimination of barriers which 
separated people from each other for decades and even centuries. 
  Clinton has decided to end 30 years of confrontations 
between 
Hanoi and Washington. This will entail a high political cost 
for him in view of the wounds which that war inflicted on U.S. 
society, but he has paid more heed to the unanimous opinion of 
his advisers, including the military, who had been advising him 
to lift the embargo, and this shows his repeated concern to 
serve the cause of peace. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-39290 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu031_n_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-031 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

