<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Macedonia, Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1402201294 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1600 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1402201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During a joint news conference today with Alfred 
Serreqi, his Albanian counterpart who is officially visiting 
Greece, Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias said the resumption 
of the Athens-Skopje dialogue depends on whether the well-known 
prerequisites set by Greece are accepted. 
  Papoulias expressed reservations about the stabilizing role 
that Skopje can play, a view supported by Serreqi. 
Specifically, using the word "Macedonia," Serreqi described 
Skopje as a factor of stability in the region. Papoulias 
stressed: With its constitution, symbols, and unceasing 
propaganda, Skopje is strengthening those circles that do not 
want peace and stability in the region. He noted: If Skopje 
does not accept Greece's conditions, the dialogue will be 
suspended, as the prime minister has said. The Greek position 
cannot be misinterpreted. 
  The Albanian foreign minister is visiting Athens within the 
framework of political dialogue between the European Union [EU] 
and Albania. During their meeting, Papoulias and Serreqi 
discussed Albania's relations with the EU, its accession to 
various programs, and support for its effort to democratize and 
change institutions. 
  The two ministers also discussed the crisis in the former 
Yugoslavia, especially the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
Serreqi said the Albanian Government supports NATO's decision 
on air strikes against Bosnia-Herzegovina and added that Tirana 
disagrees with dividing that country into three parts. 
  Asked of the Albanian Government's draft bill on education, 
which is expected to include provisions for the teaching of the 
Greek language, Serreqi said the provisions of international 
treaties and the CSCE will be considered. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

