<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Social Affairs Minister Juncker Resigns </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1402131694 Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE in Danish 12 Feb 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM1402131694 </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Danish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Bo Jeppesen and Bent Winther: "Juncker Triggers </F>
Crisis Among Center Democrats"] 
  [Excerpts] The Center Democrats' Bente Juncker, who 
yesterday was forced to give up her dream job after only two 
weeks as social affairs minister, is now being threatened by her 
own colleagues in the Center Democrat Folketing group. 
  Bente Juncker was forced to resign after having circulated 
unproven sexual insinuations about Poul Thofner, the head of the 
Fyrreparken institute for the mentally subnormal in Naestved. 
He is now threatening a court case for defamation. 
  Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen (Social Democratic 
Party) 
did not protest at the social affairs minister's resignation: 
"I agree with Bente Juncker's decision," he said. "It was a 
sad day, but let us look forward instead of being too 
depressed." [passage omitted] 
  The new social affairs minister will be former Center 
Democrat Folketing deputy Yvonne Herlov Andersen. She comes 
from a job as head of an institution for the mentally 
handicapped and is the first trained social worker to fill the 
post. 

</TEXT>

