<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Considers Publishing Military Doctrine </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602122894 Berlin DIE WELT in German 16 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU1602122894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "rmc": "Naumann Asking for Understanding"] </F>
  [Text] Moscow -- "At the moment, NATO is the only working 
defense organization in Europe. It must not be weakened under 
any circumstances." These were the words of the inspector 
general of the Bundeswehr, General Naumann, talking to officers 
of the Moscow General Staff Academy yesterday. 
  He was trying to make his Russian audience appreciate that 
for the Europeans, the alliance is an opportunity to develop a 
"European security and defense identity." The Partnership for 
Peace program initiated by NATO should offer all states outside 
NATO an opportunity for cooperation, including Russia. In 
unmistakably clear words, Naumann said: "It is the NATO of 16 
that decides on admitting new members." In his opinion, Russia 
cannot join. 
  Talking to Russian Chief of Staff Kolesnikov, Naumann got 
the 
impression that the "the NATO Partnership for Peace program is 
viewed increasingly positive." In Naumann's view, the fact that 
the Russian military leadership seems to be taking the West's 
warnings to heart and is thinking of publishing the full text of 
the military doctrine adopted last autumn is almost sensational. 
During the German-Russian General Staff talks scheduled to be 
held in Bonn mid- March, the German side wants to show its 
appreciation for the Russians' openness by affording them 
unrestricted access to the Bundeswehr's secrete defense concept. 

</TEXT>

