<F P=100> SWITZERLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Ready To Improve Ties With Turkey </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0402160794 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1451 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0402160794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Strasbourg, Feb 4 (A.A) -- Swiss Interior Minister 
Ruth Dreifuss said on Friday [4 February] that they attached 
importance to relations with Turkey, adding that "we hope Turkey 
will send an ambassador to Bern soon." 
  Last year, diplomatic relations became tense and Ankara and 
Bern drew their ambassadors back upon the outlawed separatist 
terrorist PKK [Workers Party of Kurdistan] organization's attack 
on Turkish Consulate in Bern. 
  Dreifuss who came to Strasbourg to attend a Council of 
Europe 
ministerial meeting on drugs, speaking to an AA reporter said 
Switzerland was ready to improve bilateral relations with Turkey. 
  Recalling Swiss justice authorities' request for 
investigation on Turkish Consulate in Bern, Dreifuss said 
Turkish Government did not want the investigation to be done and 
drew its ambassador back. 
  Dreifuss defended the idea that it would be more difficult 
to 
put the separatist terrorist organization under control if they 
ban this organization adding that the Swiss Government will 
never allow any terrorist organization to create violence. 

</TEXT>

