<H3> <TI>   Resolution Sought for Regional Aid Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20354B </F>
<F P=103> 94P20354B </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Editorial Report] In the final phase of the accession 
negotiations, EU and Swedish negotiators are trying to find a 
way to secure regional aid for the sparsely populated northern 
part of Sweden. Ingrid Hedstrom writes in the 17 January 
Stockholm Swedish daily DAGENS NYHETER on page 7 that at the end 
of December the EU had offered to classify the area as a first 
priority region, allowing it to receive EU support reserved for 
underdeveloped regions. To be classified as such, however, an 
area's GNP must be only 75 percent of the EU average; the GNP of 
the Swedish northern provinces is 113 percent of the average. 
Swedish negotiators are looking for new ways to calculate the 
GNP so that it will fall below the limit. They have excluded 
revenue from hydropower stations located on northern rivers, 
which raise GNP figures but do little to increase the welfare of 
the region. In this way, they succeeded in lowering the figure 
to below the 75-percent limit in certain areas. According to a 
14 January Stockholm Swedish daily DAGENS NYHETER article on 
page 7 by Ingrid Hedstrom, EU officials are also trying to come 
up with new criteria for their regional policy. An EU source 
told the newspaper: "They [the new criteria] must be idiotproof 
and watertight, and applicable only to Sweden, Norway, and 
Finland. One possibility would be to use a certain latitude 
line as a criterion." 


