<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   President, Politicians Comment After Council Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1502185994 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1502185994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Glavkos Kliridhis said the National 
Council unanimously suggested that the Greek Cypriot side should 
attend the proximity talks beginning on 17 February. Kliridhis 
was speaking after a lengthy National Council meeting today to 
discuss the substance of the Cyprus issue and the 
confidence-building measures [CBM's]. 
  The president said there were some differences in views and 
that some people suggested disengagement from the CBM's while 
others said we should discuss them but on the basis of some 
principles. Answering questions, Kliridhis said that when he 
attends the talks, his goal will be to discuss those points that 
the UN secretary general refers to as the basic points in his 
set of ideas. He said he expects Butrus-Ghali to announce these 
points tonight. 
  DISI [Democratic Rally] Chairman Ioannis Matsis said we are 
now facing decisive developments for the future of the country, 
so our side must move carefully. On the handling of the 
discussion of the Cyprus issue, Matsis said there has been a 
noteworthy change with the European Union observer's 
intervention and presence at the talks. He continued: We 
believe that the observer's reports, as his orders say, should 
be in line with European law. Matsis added that DISI is 
determined to support the president during this decisive course 
for the Cyprus issue so as to hold talks in the most effective 
manner. 
  AKEL [Restorative Party of the Working People] Secretary 
General Dhimitrios Khristofias said that when the president 
decided to participate in the proximity talks he should have 
manipulated the discussion to include the substance of the 
Cyprus issue. Khristofias said that AKEL has no intention of 
covering up the faits accomplis created by the president, adding 
that AKEL interprets any reference to the substance of the 
Cyprus issue as a return to discussing Butrus-Ghali's ideas. 
  DIKO [Democratic Party] Chairman Spiros Kiprianou reiterated 
that he considers the CBM's as unacceptable and very dangerous. 
He said: We are afraid that if the CBM's are implemented they 
will form the basis of an overall Cyprus solution. He added 
that the measures solve the illegal regime's problems and 
therefore Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot side have no reason to 
pursue a reasonable Cyprus solution. The DIKO chairman said 
disengagement from the measures is necessary, adding that his 
party made suggestions on how the president should handle the 
issue. 
  Socialist party EDEK [United Democratic Union of Cyprus] 
Chairman Vasos Lissaridhis said he pointed out ways to disengage 
from the measures, adding that all the prerequisites exist for a 
return to discussing the substance of the Cyprus issue. He said 
he believes the contrasting views expressed in the National 
Council strengthen the president's negotiating position. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

