<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Begins `New Initiative' in Serbia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1502140894 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1502140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Greece assumes a new initiative to avert the West's 
threatening military engagement in Bosnia-Herzegovina. Foreign 
Minister Karolos Papoulias today went to Belgrade to promote 
this initiative. Papoulias will meet Serbian President Slobodan 
Milosevic to discuss the developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina 
which are at an extremely critical point. 
  Before his departure from Ellinikon Airport, Foreign 
Minister 
Papoulias stressed: I am going to Belgrade on a very important 
trip, especially because it is just a few days, a few hours, 
before the expiration of NATO's ultimatum. These are the last 
intensive efforts we can make to save the peace. I believe, 
Papoulias added, that the talks we have will be important and 
productive in the direction we all want, that is, to promote the 
European Union's plan and the peace process. There is no other 
way, he said, and added: The road to peace is one way and 
whoever thinks that with the use of force they will manage 
something better than what we have achieved thus far, I think he 
does not evaluate the situation correctly. 
  According to REUTER, it is possible that Papoulias will not 
return to Athens but will visit another capital in Europe. 

</TEXT>

