<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Returns From Belgrade, Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1602080594 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 0500 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1602080594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias returned late 
last night from Belgrade where he had long meetings with Serbian 
President Slobodan Milosevic and Bosnian Serb leader Radovan 
Karadzic. 
  Papoulias stressed: There is much hope that we can avoid the 
worst in the Bosnia-Herzegovina crisis, as reports on the 
withdrawal of heavy weapons from around Sarajevo are hopeful. 
However, he noted this process is not the exclusive obligation 
of the Serbs and the Muslims should do the same. Papoulias 
expressed Greece's fears for the chain reaction a general 
conflict would have in the Balkans and in Europe, and added that 
he does not believe air strikes can bring peace. 
  The Greek presidency of the European Union [EU] also is 
contemplating calling a meeting of the EU Council of Foreign 
Ministers before the deadline of NATO's ultimatum, the Greek 
foreign minister said. Responding to a question if Athens will 
exercise a veto in NATO on the air strikes, he said that Greece 
is contemplating and will use all available means to avoid a 
wider conflict. Papoulias also stressed that he discussed the 
possibility of the war spreading to the south with Milosevic, 
and underlined that something like this would be a tragic 
development and the beginning of an armed conflict that would 
have wider consequences in Europe. Responding to another 
question, the foreign minister said that the Greeks living in 
Serbia are safe. They consider it their second homeland and 
have no need to leave. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

