<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rasmussen: Tanks Bound for Tuzla, Not Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1502174394 Paris AFP in English 1727 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1502174394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Copenhagen, Feb 15 (AFP) -- A unit of tanks that 
has been trying to reach UN troops in the Bosnian enclave of 
Tuzla for five months will not be diverted to Sarajevo, Danish 
Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen said Tuesday [15 February]. 
  Speaking at a meeting with party leaders on the situation in 
the former Yugoslavia, Rasmussen said if the United Nations 
wanted to change its plans for the Danish Leopard tanks the 
question would have to be referred back to parliament here. 
[passage omitted] 
  Rasmussen said that in any event Sweden wanted the Danish 
troops in Tuzla so it could move some armoured troop carriers to 
Sarajevo. 
  The Leopards will first head for Tomislavgrad in southwest 
Bosnia, which is under the control of Bosnian Croat militia. 
  Rasmussen said he expected that the Croats would let the 
tanks through. 

</TEXT>

