<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clark Arrives To Participate in Talks, Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1502220894 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 2000 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1502220894 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Joe Clark, the UN secretary general's special 
representative in Cyprus, arrived tonight to participate in the 
proximity talks scheduled to begin on 17 February and said the 
Cyprus issue has reached a new, very serious phase. He added 
that progress has been achieved and if we continue in the same 
manner, we can deal with the substance of the issue and make 
progress. 
  Before making his statement, Clark met briefly with UN 
envoys 
Gustave Feissel and John Paul Kavanagh. In his statement, Clark 
reiterated that the international community is satisfied that 
both sides have shown goodwill, adding that interest has been 
expressed on the higher levels of the international community. 
  Answering a question, Clark said he can give assurances that 
implementation of the confidence-building measures [CBM's] will 
not constitute a Cyprus solution. He added that the CBM's are 
the principle that will lead to an appropriate climate to 
discuss the substance of the Cyprus issue. Answering another 
question, Clark said he disagrees with the view that the CBM's 
are destructive, adding that his mission is to promote a 
procedure that is supported by the United Nations. 
  Clark said it is important to achieve progress by the end of 
February, when the UN secretary general will submit his report, 
so that the UN Security Council can evaluate the whole issue. 

</TEXT>

