<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Has More Plutonium </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702111094 Vienna KURIER in German 17 Feb 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU1702111094 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna KURIER </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ingrid Steiner: "North Korea's Pawn Continues To </F>
Be Well Hidden"] 
  [Excerpt] When the delegation of experts of the 
International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] inspect the North 
Korean nuclear facilities on Yongbon, every step will be 
carefully observed. They will not be allowed to deviate a 
single inch from the determined route or take a closer look at 
an earth mound or a tree at the giant plant. The strictly 
communist North Korea will not allow any inspections of the site 
where the IAEA expects underground secret nuclear plants to be 
located. 
  "We know that the two plants exist," IAEA spokesman David 
Kyd 
told KURIER. "They are clearly recognized on satellite 
pictures. They are located right in the center of the Yongbon 
site." 
  However, North Korea categorically denies everything. The 
plants in question are merely "military facilities." 
  In the seven declared nuclear plants where the IAEA will be 
granted access, North Korea cannot build an "atomic bomb"; it 
can only produce fissile material. "North Korea started its 
nuclear program 20 years ago. We are absolutely certain that it 
possesses more plutonium than Pyongyang admits," Kyd stressed. 
Only 5-8 kg are needed to produce a single atomic bomb. 
  According to Kyd, only the United States can exert the 
required pressure needed to ensure the inspection of the two 
secret plants. "The IAEA does not have any instruments; only 
Washington has something to offer" -- that is economic aid for 
extremely poor North Korea or the U.S. promise to renounce the 
large-scale maneuver, planned together with South Korea. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

